SIMPLE: near
RECORDS: 5

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Near
<hw>Near</hw> <pr>(n⟦emac⟧r)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>ne⟦aacute⟧r</ets>, compar. of <ets>ne⟦aacute⟧h</ets> nigh. See
<er>Nigh</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>At a little distance, in place,
time, manner, or degree; not remote; nigh.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My wife! my traitress! let her not come <qex>near</qex> me.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Nearly; almost; well-nigh.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Near</xex> twenty years ago.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Shak.</au>
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Near</xex> a fortnight ago.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Addison.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Near</qex> about the yearly value of the land.</q>
<rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Closely; intimately.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Far and near</b></col>, <cd>at a distance and close by;
throughout a whole region.</cd> -- <col><b>To come near to</b></col>,
<cd>to want but little of; to approximate to.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧Such a sum he
found would <xex>go near to</xex> ruin him.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Addison.</au></rj> -- <col><b>Near the wind</b></col>
<fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>close to the wind; closehauled.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Near</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Near
<hw>Near</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos>
<adjf>Nearer</adjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos>
<adjf>Nearest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[See <er>Near</er>,
<pos>adv.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Not far distant in time, place,
or degree; not remote; close at hand; adjacent; neighboring; nigh.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧As one <xex>near</xex> death.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He served great Hector, and was ever <qex>near</qex>,⟦br⟧
Not with his trumpet only, but his spear.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Closely connected or related.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She is thy father's <qex>near</qex> kinswoman.</q> <rj><qau>Lev.
xviii. 12.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Close to one's interests, affection, etc.; touching,
or affecting intimately; intimate; dear; <as>as, a <ex>near</ex>
friend</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Close to anything followed or imitated; not free,
loose, or rambling; <as>as, a version <ex>near</ex> to the
original</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>So as barely to avoid or pass injury or loss; close;
narrow{3}; <as>as, a <ex>near</ex> escape; a <ex>near</ex>
miss</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Next to the driver, when he is on foot; in the United
States, on the left of an animal or a team; <as>as, the <ex>near</ex>
ox; the <ex>near</ex> leg</as>. See <cref>Off side</cref>, under
<er>Off</er>, <pos>a</pos>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>Immediate; direct; close; short.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The
<xex>nearest</xex> way.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>Close-fisted; parsimonious.</def> <mark>[Obs. or
Low, Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Near</xex> may properly be followed by
<xex>to</xex> before the thing approached; but more frequently
<xex>to</xex> is omitted, and the adjective or the adverb is regarded as
a preposition. The same is also true of the word
<xex>nigh</xex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Nigh; close; adjacent; proximate; contiguous;
present; ready; intimate; familiar; dear.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Near</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Near
<hw>Near</hw>, <pos>prep.</pos> <def>Adjacent to; close by; not far
from; nigh; <as>as, the ship sailed <ex>near</ex> the land</as>. See the
Note under <er>near</er>, <pos>a.</pos></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Near</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Near
<hw>Near</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Neared</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n</pos>
<conjf>Nearing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[See <er>Near</er>,
<pos>adv.</pos>]</ety> <def>To approach; to come nearer; <as>as, the
ship <ex>neared</ex> the land</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Near</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Near
<hw>Near</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To draw near; to
approach.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A speck, a mist, a shape, I wist!⟦br⟧
And still it <qex>neared</qex>, and <qex>neared</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Coleridge.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Nearctic</ent>⟦br⟧
